thread.title: Go downtown to Midtown

title: Go downtown to Midtown
text:
680 George Street, in hot demand Photo: Michel O'Sullivan
DEXUS Property and Mirvac have set the tone for the office markets in the coming year, saying demand is high and vacancy levels are forecast to contract with improved leasing deals.
While there will be some headwinds in the coming year as more of Barangaroo South is opened at Darling Harbour, the 2017 and 2018 years will see the reverse with demand outstripping supply.
According to the analysts at Citi said post the DEXUS result, the clear on-going demand for investment grade assets should result in a significant lift in office and industrial asset values.
"We have moved to capture these in our DEXUS valuation. This also augurs well for Investa Office, Mirvac, Charter Hall, Abacus Property Goodman, GPT Group and Stockland," they said.
Advertisement "More broadly, we expect Australian real estate investment trusts AREITs will increasingly look to capitalise on this strength in asset prices by selling non-core assets into it."
GPT and Stockland will report next week.
The improved office conditions in Sydney, were also evidenced by the Mirvac result, where the new development at 200 George Street is well leased. Ernst & Young will be the anchor, with Mirvac also moving in as its new head quarters.
But agents say the demand is also strong in the Midtown and southern precincts of the Sydney CBD due to the areas' rental profile and busy atmosphere which distinguish them from the traditional financial core of the CBD.
CBRE has recently been involved with a series of lease agreements in the CBD's mid-town region, including spaces at 66 Goulburn Street, 2 Park Street and 680 George Street, where Ernst & Young are moving from, which reflect this trend.
Chris Fisher, CBRE director office services, said a notable increase in tenant interest for offices space towards the Midtown and southern precincts has been identified.
"The vibrant atmosphere, access to retail amenities, proximity to public transport and availability of quality stock at competitive rental rates is underpinning the increasing tenant interest in the area," Mr Fisher said.
"World Square for example provides a comprehensive retail experience consisting of fashion, restaurants and bars in the heart of one of the most densely populated areas in Australia. There is always activity in this part of town, whether during the day or after hours."
Mr Fisher has also worked on leasing at 66 Goulburn Street to Copyright Agency Credit Investment Ombudsman, OMG and ICity Realty, among others.
"With the withdrawal of office stock or threat of withdrawal for residential conversions, tenants are being driven to locate alternative commercial sites, thereby increasing competition and demand in the Midtown and southern Sydney markets."
The Midtown and southern sectors have further been successful in attracting tenants from suburban locations and the city fringe.
"High quality office buildings providing accommodations at competitive rental rates have encouraged the migration of outlying tenants such as Tabcorp and Freelancer to 680 George Street and Unilever to 2 Park Street," Mr Fisher said.
